  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a pure Python codebase (async fetch pipeline + SQLite store, no web frontend), so there's no React to analyze — I focused on the four categories that actually apply: N+1 queries, caching, memory, and redundant computation.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-97` (`Store.diff`)\n\nWith 132 sources configured (`sources.yaml`) and several fetchers paginating up to 400-800 jobs each (Amazon, Microsoft, Apple, Netflix), a single run can produce many thousands of `Job` objects. `diff()` does one `SELECT` + one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` **per job, in a Python loop**:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        ...\n```\n\nFor N=10,000 jobs that's 10,000+ round trips to SQLite every run, each paying Python/sqlite3 cursor overhead. Fix: batch-load existing hashes in one query, then use `executemany` for the writes.\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    # SQLite caps bound params (~32k) — chunk if a run ever approaches that\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(self.conn.execute(q, chunk))\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = job.content_hash          # compute once, reuse below\n        if job.key not in existing:\n            new.append(job)\n            insert_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif existing[job.key] != h:\n            changed.append(job)\n            update_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,...,:now,:now)\", insert_rows)\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(N/900 + 3) statements.\n\n### 2. Redundant regex compilation — `filters.py:11-27, 44-55`\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match(job, ...)` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside that per-job call**. The same include/exclude keyword lists get recompiled into `re.Pattern` objects for every single job:\n\n```python\ndef _compile(words): \n    return [re.compile(...) for w in words if w]   # runs once PER JOB, not once per run\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):\n```\n\nFix: compile once per `filter_jobs` call and pass compiled patterns down.\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nFor a few thousand jobs with a handful of keywords this is thousands of wasted `re.compile` calls (compilation is far more expensive than the match itself).\n\n### 3. Small redundant computation — `models.py:66-69` + `store.py`\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a `@property` that hashes `title|location|url|department` on every access via SHA-256. In the \"changed\" path it's computed once for the comparison in `diff()` (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and then computed **again** inside `_update` → `to_row()` → `self.content_hash`. Cheap individually, but easy to avoid — compute it once per job and pass it through (folded into the `diff()` rewrite above via `h = job.content_hash`).\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity — full-board re-fetch every run\n\nPer the commit history this runs on a 12h cron. Several fetchers pull the **entire board** every run with no conditional-request support — e.g. `fetch_amazon`/`fetch_microsoft` (max_pages=40, 10/page = 400 requests worth of JSON), `fetch_apple` (max_pages=10, ~200 roles, board is ~6,400 total per the comment). None of the `_get_json`/`_get_text` calls send `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`, and there's no short-lived response cache, so a re-run 12h later refetches byte-identical pages for boards that changed by a handful of postings.\n\nTwo low-risk wins:\n- Where the ATS returns `Last-Modified`/`ETag` (worth checking per-source — Greenhouse/Ashby's `boards-api` often does), thread it through `_request` and skip re-parsing on a 304.\n- For paginated fetchers, the `seen`-dedup loops already stop at the first page with no *new* IDs — but that's dedup within a run, not caching across runs. Nothing currently short-circuits early when this run's page 1 is identical to last run's page 1.\n\nThis is lower priority than #1/#2 since it changes network behavior (needs verifying each ATS actually honors conditional headers) — flagging it as an opportunity rather than a concrete diff.\n\n### 5. Memory leaks\n\nDidn't find any. `httpx.AsyncClient` lifecycle in `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:1126-1147`) is correctly scoped with `try/finally` + `aclose()`, and `Store` connections are opened/closed via context managers everywhere (`pipeline.py:42`, `agent.py:_store`/`cmd_db_mark`/`cmd_report_num`). The `seen: set[str]` accumulators in paginated fetchers are bounded by `max_pages`, so no unbounded growth.\n\n---\n\n**Priority**: fix #1 (`store.diff` N+1) first — it's the one that scales with total job count and runs every single pipeline execution. #2 is a quick, safe win. #3 is negligible on its own but falls out of the #1 rewrite for free. #4 is worth a follow-up investigation, not an immediate change.\n",
